[3] Diarrhea, fatal - Indonesia (West Sulawesi)
Date: Sat 15 Nov 2008
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2008/11/15/diarrhea-kills-12-west-sulawesi.html>


A diarrhea outbreak has killed 12 people in Polewali Mandar regency,
West Sulawesi since October 2008, with nearly 200 residents seeking
treatment in hospitals and local Puskesmas (community health
centers). Polewali Mandar Health Agency head, Ahmad Azis, said
Tuesday that out of more than 1500 residents who sought treatment,
around 150 remain hospitalized due to the illness. He said the
outbreak was the worst in 4 years to hit Polewali Mandar, and had
spread to the districts of Pambusuang, Mapilli, Batu Panga,
Kanreapia, and Pekkabata.

"Therefore we have classified the 5 districts under the extraordinary
occurrence status, because the number of cases has doubled from last
month [October 2008], and the overall instance of diarrhea is far
greater than in 2007," Azis told The Jakarta Post over the phone.

The outbreak occurred after floods inundated the area, forcing
residents to rely on contaminated water for consumption and cleaning.
Reports from the area show that many residents in the flooded areas
were not boiling their water adequately, or were simply consuming it
directly from the contaminated sources.

[Byline: Andi Hajramurni]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[West Sulawesi or Sulawesi Barat (short form Sulbar) is a province of
Indonesia, created in 2004. It is on the island of Sulawesi
(formerly, Celebes) and includes the regencies (kabupaten) of
Polewali Mandar, Mamasa, Majene, Mamuju, and Mamuju Utara, which were
formerly part of South Sulawesi. A map of the area and more
information can be found at
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Sulawesi>. - Mod.LL]

