[6] Cholera - Zimbabwe (Matabeleland South)
Date: Tue 18 Nov 2008
Source: The Chronicle [edited]
<http://www.chronicle.co.zw/inside.aspx?sectid=312&cat=1>


A serious cholera outbreak has hit Beitbridge District in
Matabeleland South, killing 36 people, while 431 have been diagnosed
as having the disease, Chronicle learned yesterday [17 Nov 2008].

Confirming the outbreak, the acting district medical officer for
Beitbridge, Dr Takaitei Kanongora, said the epidemic was detected on
Friday night [14 Nov 2008] following the admission of a Chegutu woman
to Beitbridge District Hospital. The woman involved in cross-border
trade, intended to cross into South Africa when she succumbed to
cholera. It is suspected that the now deceased woman, who was selling
amazhanje, could have eaten them resulting in severe vomiting and diarrhoea.

"There is a serious outbreak of cholera in Beitbridge and we have
since taken biological (stool) samples to our laboratory, which
eventually confirmed that. Initially we had recorded 8 deaths but
however this morning (17 Nov 2008) the number of the casualties has
increased to 36 and we have admitted 431 people at Beitbridge
Hospital," said Dr Kanongora. He said due to inadequate health
personnel and resources they had been forced to close the only
district hospital to other cases except cholera-related ailments.

"We had to clear the hospital wards to create space for the cholera
patients and therefore we had to close the hospital to other cases
except cholera and we are referring them (other cases) to other
health centres largely because of lack of equipment and staff as we
are now prioritising cholera," he said.

Medecins Sans Frontieres (MSF), a non-governmental organization, and
the International Organisation for Migration (IOM) have deployed
their staff to assist in fighting the epidemic. The 2 organisations
also supplied the hospital with medical kits such as gloves, tablets,
and protective garments for the health staff.

Cases of cholera in Beitbridge District were last reported in 2003.
Travelers passing through the border post have also been put on high
alert following the outbreak. Beitbridge border post is reported to
be the busiest point of entry in sub-Saharan Africa with a huge
volume of both human and motor traffic passing through everyday.

[Byline: Mashudu Netsianda]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As can be seen on a map at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/zimbabwe.pdf>, the
areas are in extreme southern Zimbabwe bordering on South Africa.

Much of the recent cholera activity in Zimbabwe has been in the
capital Harare and other northern areas. - Mod.LL]

